NOTES_NUMBERS_33_36 = {
    33: {
        2: 'WRITTEN RECORD: \'Moses recorded their starting places\' -- one of the explicit statements that Moses authored portions of the Pentateuch. This travel itinerary is an official document, recorded by command. The 42 stations from Egypt to the plains of Moab trace the entire wilderness journey.',
        4: 'JUDGMENTS ON THEIR GODS: The plagues were not merely against Egypt but against Egypt\'s gods (Exod 12:12). Each plague targeted a specific deity: the Nile (Hapi), frogs (Heqet), sun darkened (Ra), death of firstborn (Pharaoh himself, considered divine). The Exodus is a divine council confrontation -- YHWH defeats the gods of Egypt and liberates their slaves.',
        9: 'TWELVE SPRINGS, SEVENTY PALMS: Twelve for the tribes, seventy for the elders (or the nations of Gen 10). Elim is a place of abundance between trials -- a divine rest stop. God provides refreshment between challenges.',
        52: 'DESTROY ALL: The command to destroy figured stones (maskkiyyot -- carved images), molten images, and high places is total. No syncretism, no accommodation, no preservation of Canaanite religious infrastructure. The land must be purged of false worship before it can be inhabited by YHWH\'s people.',
        55: 'PRICKS AND THORNS: If Israel fails to drive out the inhabitants, they will become \'pricks in your eyes and thorns in your sides.\' This prophecy was fulfilled exactly -- Judges records the ongoing trouble caused by the peoples Israel failed to expel. Compromise with idolatry always produces lasting pain.',
    },
    34: {
        2: 'BOUNDARIES OF CANAAN: The promised land\'s borders are precisely defined -- south from the Dead Sea to the Brook of Egypt, west along the Mediterranean coast, north to the entrance of Hamath, east from Hazar-enan down to the Sea of Chinnereth (Galilee) and the Jordan. These boundaries have never been fully possessed by Israel but remain the promise. The land belongs to God (Lev 25:23) and is given by God.',
        11: 'SEA OF CHINNERETH: The Sea of Galilee -- the lake where Jesus would walk on water, calm the storm, call His first disciples, and appear after His resurrection. The eastern boundary of the promised land passes through the place where the Messiah would begin His ministry.',
        19: 'CALEB ASSIGNED TO JUDAH: Of the twelve leaders appointed to divide the land, only Caleb is a name from the older generation. The faithful spy who followed God fully is now, 45 years later, assigned to oversee Judah\'s inheritance. Faithfulness has its reward -- delayed, but certain.',
    },
    35: {
        6: 'CITIES OF REFUGE: Six cities where an accidental killer can flee from the blood avenger (go\'el haddam). The blood avenger was the nearest male relative of the deceased, obligated to execute justice. The cities of refuge provide due process -- the accused must be tried by the congregation (v.24) before the blood avenger can act. This is a remarkable system of legal protection in the ancient world.',
        11: 'UNINTENTIONAL KILLING: The distinction between murder (intentional) and manslaughter (unintentional) is critical to biblical justice. Murder requires execution; manslaughter requires exile in a city of refuge. The standard of evidence is multiple witnesses (v.30). No one dies on a single testimony.',
        25: 'UNTIL THE DEATH OF THE HIGH PRIEST: The accidental killer must remain in the city of refuge until the high priest dies. Then he is free to return home. CHRIST TYPOLOGY: This is one of the most profound types in the Old Testament. The manslayer\'s exile ends when the high priest dies. Christ, our High Priest, died -- and through His death, all who have fled to Him for refuge are set free. The death of the High Priest liberates the exiles. Hebrews 6:18 speaks of believers who \'have taken refuge\' -- we have fled to Christ, our city of refuge, and His death as High Priest has set us permanently free. We will never be exiled again because our High Priest has already died and risen.',
        33: 'BLOOD POLLUTES THE LAND: Unpunished murder defiles the land where God dwells. The land is not merely real estate; it is sacred space. Innocent blood cries out from the ground (Gen 4:10) and contaminates the earth. Only the blood of the murderer can atone for the blood he shed -- or, as the New Testament reveals, the blood of Christ atones for all bloodguilt.',
        34: 'I DWELL IN THE MIDST: The final theological declaration of the cities of refuge passage -- God dwells in the land. His presence demands justice. His holiness cannot coexist with unpunished murder. The entire legal system flows from one reality: YHWH is present.',
    },
    36: {
        5: 'THE TRIBE IS RIGHT: As in chapter 27, God rules on a new legal question by affirming the petitioners. The principle: tribal inheritance must be preserved. The daughters of Zelophehad inherit, but they must marry within their tribe to prevent land transfer. Both rights (women\'s inheritance) and responsibilities (tribal preservation) are maintained.',
        7: 'NO TRANSFER BETWEEN TRIBES: The land allotment is permanent and tribal. Each tribe\'s inheritance is protected by law. THEOLOGICAL SIGNIFICANCE: The land is not merely property but covenant inheritance -- God assigned specific territory to specific families as an eternal possession. The Jubilee principle (Lev 25) ensures that even if land is sold, it returns to its original family.',
        13: 'THE BOOK\'S FINAL VERSE: Numbers ends not with triumph but with legal ordinance -- in the plains of Moab, on the threshold of the Promised Land. The generation that rebelled is dead. The new generation is counted, organized, and legally prepared. The laws of inheritance are settled. But they have not yet entered. The book ends with Israel poised on the edge of fulfillment, waiting for the command to cross the Jordan. The story continues in Deuteronomy and Joshua. CHRIST: The church lives in the same theological moment -- between promise and fulfillment, between the cross and the consummation, poised on the edge of the eternal inheritance. \'We do not yet see all things subjected to Him. But we do see Jesus\' (Heb 2:8-9). Christ is King, and the Promised Land is coming.',
    },
}
